bios.Pd2a9380: Isambard Kingdom Brunel. Brunel became involved in Bristol's merchant and commercial community in the early 1830s when he was hired to survey the city's floating harbour.  This appointment brought him into wider contact with the city's corporate patronage, specifically the members of the Bristol Chamber of Commerce, who led early debates about dock improvements and railway and steam shipping connections.  His appointment as initial surveyor and later engineer of the Great Western Railway was a result of contact with this group, as was his involvement with the city's Atlantic steamshipping endeavours. Spearheaded by Thomas Guppy, the Bristol group decided to fully develop transatlantic steamshipping in 1836, after other initial attempts in the UK began to gain capital.  Brunel was critical in the creation of the SS Great Western, the first ship of the Great Western Steamship Company, by guiding the company toward Joshua Field of Maudslay, Sons & Field, as builder of the ships' engines.  Field was in turn connected to the leading edge of marine engineering, through figures such as Oliver Lang (structural design) and Samuel Hall (engine efficiencies).  Brunel superindented the production the Great Western's engines, but there is no direct documentray evidence that he led the ship's design.  His role was managerial and social.  In the Great Britain, Brunel's role was more central, being involved in core elements of design, and the critical decision to build the ship in iron and to adopt a propeller.  Brunel's report convincing the directors to do so recently gained UNESCO status for its historical significance.  Brunel's correspondence when building the Great Britain shows a great appetite for the expertise of other contemporaries, but also the first signs of rejection of sound advice in favour of his own approach.  This theme became characteristic in the building of the Great Eastern, in which Brunel attempted total control of design and planning, and accepted tenders and approaches from companies and individuals who submitted designs in accordance with these plans, but who were not best placed in the world of marine engineering.  The building of the Great Eastern also saw Brunel abandon searches for, and changes in, the conceptual layout of the vessel in the search of greatest performance, being wedded firmly to its original concept and design throughout.

bios.P97b1859: The Cunard Line, launched in 1840 as a British government mail carrier on the North Atlantic, was the first line to succesfully run a continuous service of multiple steamships between Britain and North America.  The firm was an early rival of the GWSSco., who had also bid for the mail contract. In 1855, Cunard advised the Liverpool Corporation that it was unnecessary to widen the lock gates at Liverpool for the Great Eastern.  The Corporation, which had previously been contacted on behalf of the ESN and on behalf of local railways, asking whether the locks would be wide enough for the Great Eastern, had intimated that it would accomodate the ship, but took Cunards advice as 'the most experienced in steam navigation of the port of Liverpool'.  Cunard's advice against widening the locks may have contributed to the Great Eastern not using that port - an enormous disadvantage to its commerce.

bios.Pde8bb3b: Thomas Guppy.  Bristol sugar merchant and manufacturer.  Founding member of the Bristol Chamber of Commerce, Guppy was one of four individuals credited with the founding of the Great Western Railway.  In contemporary sources, notably the first AGM of the Great Western Steamship Co., as well as the writings of Christopher Claxton, he is also credited as the original projector of the Great Western Steamship Company.  This credit existed in local Bristol press until well into the 20th century, the idea of Brunel being progenitor of the GWSSco. emerging only with the biography written by his son in 1870, and later emergence of Brunel as a nationally renowned figure.  As the only member of the BCC and GWSSco. who had experience with North Atlantic trade (as owner of a sugar refinery in New York), and as the earliest known proponent of rail and steam connections for Bristol, Guppy's founding role is both logical and clear.  Guppy served as director of Great Western Steamship Company from its first inception, and later as resident engineer during the latter half of the Great Britain's construction, working closely with Brunel and William Patterson.

bios.Pd144fe2: Howard corresponded with Brunel in 1857 about the pre-heating of steam to increase efficiency in marine engines.  Howard had recently published work in Mechanics Magazine, and Brunel commented to him that 'until new methods are invented that can be applied to the big ship' (Great Eastern), he would continue to use the method of steam jacketing to pre-heat steam for its engines.  Steam jacketing was ultimately found to be the root of the funnel explosion which killed three men during the Great Eastern's trials. In 1854, John Elder, a Glaswegian marine engineer, had created and deployed the safer and more efficient compound engine-system, which emerged as the desired industry model by the time of the Great Eastern's first voyage across the Atlantic.

bios.Pb03c159: During Lancefield Forge's troubles with fabricating the main crankshaft of the Great Eastern, Longsdon wrote to Brunel to offer a steel forging, which would be both lighter and stronger. Longsdon provided accompanying information of similar weights of steel forged by his firm for other engineers and for the French government.  His firm was Krupp's Cast Steel Works, a progenitor of the largest European steelmaker in history.  Brunel replied that he could not possibly risk a new material on such a key part of the ship, that he was 'doubtful very much would come of it [steel]', but nonetheless asked for extensive technical data.  The offer, and refusal, of a new material for the crankshaft which would have solved a significant technical problem with the Great Eastern is a clear example of the ship's concept being too large for existing materials and techniques, but too oversized and expensive to be innovative.
bios.P142bcd2: Josiah Lorkin - who was not a prior associate - wrote to Brunel on 3 December, 1856 with comparative calorific and cost data on Welsh and Pennsylvanian Anthracite, demonstrating the economy, on the Atlantic run, of collecting return coals from Philadelphia, and the inefficiency of carrying out-and-return loads of Welsh coal.  The letter was not reciprocated, but is one of the most significant pieces of correspondence in the Great Eastern project.  It demonstrates firstly that a U.S. route for the Great Eastern was both widely accepted and publicly known by the mid-point of the ships' construction, negating the need for a vessel engineered to carry coals to India or Australia, and secondly, that both Brunel and the ESN were ignorant of marine fueling on the Atlantic route, which made ships with oversized fuel capacity unneccesary and inefficient.  It is a letter that suggests that, even by the mid-point of its construction, the Great Eastern as a project and concept had become obsolete.
